# Logic and Arguments

![Tweedledum and
Tweedledee](http://reggienet.illinoisstate.edu/access/content/user/desanso/public/img/tweedledum.png){alt="Alice
approaches Tweedledum and Tweedledee (an illustration from Alice in
Wonderland)"}
[PD](attributions#tweedledum.png){.attribution target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"}

:::: epigraph
"Contrariwise," continued Tweedledee, "if it was so, it might be; and if it
were so, it would be; but as it isn't, it ain't. That's logic." 

[Lewis Carroll, *Through the Looking
Glass*](https://www.gutenberg.org/files/12/12-h/12-h.htm#link2HCH0004){.source target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"}
::::
:::

## Introduction

This unit introduces our topic, logic, 
 and introduces several key concepts.

The learning objectives for this unit are:

-   You have a basic understanding of what logic is
-   You learn some of the basic concepts we use in logic, including the
    concepts of an *argument*, a *premise*, and a *conclusion*.
-   You are able to apply those concepts by analyzing simple arguments, 
    putting them into standard form.

## A Logic Puzzle

In the following clip from the movie
[Labyrinth](https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0091369/){target="_blank"
rel="noopener noreferrer"},
Sarah (played by Jennifer Connelly) attempts to solve a logic puzzle. She is
given some information, and she reasons from that information to a conclusion.
As you watch, see if you can follow Sarah's reasoning.

![Sarah's Puzzle](http://reggienet.illinoisstate.edu/access/content/user/desanso/public/vid/labyrinth-clip.mp4)

We will come back to this. But first, let's introduce some important concepts.

## Logic and Reasoning

:::vaside
[Logic]{.vocab}: the study of reasoning
:::

[Logic]{.newthought} is the study of *reasoning*. You just watched Sarah work
through a difficult piece of reasoning, and you may not be sure whether or not
her reasoning was good reasoning.

Here is a simpler example to think about. Suppose you are presented a cookie jar, and given two pieces of
information about it:

-   This jar contains both chocolate chip cookies and sugar cookies,
-   If you select any two cookies at random from this jar, at least one of them
    will be a sugar cookie.

What follows from these two pieces of information? What else can you figure
out, about the cookie jar, by reasoning from the information you have been
given?

::: illustration
![Picture of a cookie jar with a question
mark](http://reggienet.illinoisstate.edu/access/content/user/desanso/public/img/cookie-jar.png){width="162" height="230"}
[CC](attributions#cookie-jar.png){.attribution}
:::

One thing you can figure out, just by reasoning from the information you have
been given, is how many chocolate chip cookies are in the jar. Think about
it for a moment. Do you see it? 

It's okay if you don't see it. If you don't, stop reading, and give yourself a
minute or two to try to think it through, before answering the question below:

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
1 How many chocolate chip cookies are in the jar?
| At least one
| At most one
| *Exactly one
```

(Remember to click the "Submit" button. If your answer is incorrect, you will
be prompted to try again. Keep trying until you successfully submit the
correct answer.)

:::{.reaction .correct ex=1}
How did that go? Was the correct answer the answer you expected? If not, can
you see why you were wrong, and why the correct answer is what it is? 
:::

Try, as best you can, to explain *how* the correct answer, from above,
 follows from the given information:

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
2 Try to explain, as clearly as possible, how this answer follows from the two given pieces of information. 
```

:::{.reaction .correct ex=2}
If you aren't comfortable with the answer you just gave, that's okay! 
We are just getting started.
This isn't a test;
 it's just a mental exercise, 
 meant to help you start to think about *what reasoning is* and *how it works*.
:::

## Information, Sentences, and Propositions

[When you reason]{.newthought},
 you reason *from* some given pieces of information,
 *to* a new piece of information.
So reasoning is a form of *information processing*.
We will return to the *process* in a moment.
But first, what is a "piece of information"?

:::vaside
[Declarative sentence]{.vocab}: the kind of sentence that can be true or
false, because it is used to express a piece of information. Other kinds of
sentences are used to ask questions, or issue commands, and are not true or
false.
:::

A piece of information is what you communicate when you make a statement,
using a [declarative sentence]{.vocab}. For example, the declarative sentence 'Snow is
white' can be used to make the statement that snow is white, which
communicates a piece of information about the color of snow.

Not all sentences are used to express information in this way. 
For example, the interrogative sentence, 'Is snow white?', is used not to make a
statement, but to ask a question. That is, not to communicate information, but
to request information. And the imperative sentence, 'Eat the snow!', is used
to issue a command.

So there is a close connection between a piece of information and the
declarative sentence used to express it. 
But it would be a mistake to say that a declarative sentence *is* the piece of information it expresses, 
much like it would be wrong to say that the name, 'Chicago' *is* the city it
refers to. A name is a *word*, a piece of language. Chicago is a *city*, a
piece of the world.

:::aside
For entertainment purposes only:

:::youtube
<https://youtu.be/0XlO39kCQ-8>
:::
:::

Notice that the same city can have more that one name: Istanbul, for
example, has also gone by the name 'Constantinople'. This helps to show that
the name is not the city.

In the same way, the same piece of information can be expressed by more than
one declarative sentence. Each of these sentences expresses the same piece
information, about the color of snow:

::: example
| Snow is white.
| La nieve es blanca.
| Schnee ist weiß.
:::

The link between a name and the object it names is conventional: 
 the fact that 'Chicago' refers to the city it does depends on a convention, 
 established by the people who gave it that name,
 and upheld by everyone who continues to use that name for it.
In the same way, the link between a declarative sentence and the piece of
information it expresses is conventional: 
 the fact that 'Snow is white' expresses the piece of information it does, 
 about the color of snow, 
 depends on the conventions of the English language,
 established and upheld by those who speak the language.

This doesn't mean that the information itself is conventional. 
The fact that 'La nieve es blanca' expresses the information that snow is white depends on the
conventions of Spanish. And the fact that 'Snow is white' expresses the
information that snow is white depends on the conventions of English. But this
doesn't mean that the information itself depends on either the conventions of
Spanish or English, or any linguistic conventions at all.

:::vaside
[Proposition]{.vocab}: a piece of information, true or false.
:::

We've been talking about pieces of information, and how they can be expressed
by declarative sentences, but are not themselves linguistic items.
But then what are they?
In logic and philosophy, we call a "piece of information" a
[proposition]{.vocab}. This doesn't answer our question, but it gives us an
easy way to ask our question. Philosophers argue about what propositions are,
and whether or not they even exist.
But those debates go beyond the scope of this class. 

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
3  What kind of thing do you think a proposition is? Consider the true proposition that cows moo. Where is it? What is it made of? And what about the false proposition that cows meow? Where is that? What is it made of?
```

:::{.reaction .correct ex=3}
Philosophers have written whole books trying to answer these questions.

One idea is that propositions are states of affairs in the world.
On this view, the proposition that cows moo is located wherever the mooing cows are located,
 and is made up of those mooing cows.
One objection to this view is that it cannot handle false propositions:
 there are no meowing cows,
 so a proposition made up of meowing cows isn't made up of anything,
 and isn't located anywhere.

Another idea is that propositions are judgments in our minds.
One objection to this view is that,
 if the proposition that cows moo is in *my* mind,
 it cannot also be in *your* mind.
So it seems like only one of us can think about it.
Another objection is that,
 even if nobody was thinking about cows mooing,
 it would still be true that cows moo.
So that truth---that proposition---cannot be something
 that only exists in our minds.

Another idea is that propositions are abstract objects,
 that exist outside of space and time.
Many philosophers think that numbers are like this:
 the number 3, for example, exists,
 but it doesn't exist in space or time;
 it isn't something you can go visit.
One objection to this view is that it is spooky to think that there are things that exist,
 but don't exist anywhere.
:::

Pieces of information might be,
 we can agree that not all information is *good* information.
If someone tells you that there was widespread election fraud in the 2020 Presidential election, 
 that is *false*.
 *False* information is *bad* information.
And if someone tells you that COVID-19 vaccines have proved effective,
 that is *true*.
 *True* information is *good* information.
So propositions are either good or bad.
That is, they are either true or false.

## Arguments

[Reasoning]{.newthought} is a form of information processing:
 you reason *from* some given propositions, 
 *to* a new proposition.
In the cookie jar example, 
 you began with the propositions you had been given about the jar, 
 and you reasoned to the proposition that there was exactly one chocolate chip cookie in the jar.

We can represent this visually using a flow chart:

<!--
