Time for some more vocabulary.

:::vaside
| [Premises]{.vocab}: the propositions you reason from.
| [Conclusion]{.vocab}: the proposition you reason to.
| [Argument]{.vocab}: some premises and a conclusion.
:::

In logic, we call the information you reason from your [premises]{.vocab}, and
we call the information you reason to your [conclusion]{.vocab}. We call the
whole thing—the premises together with the conclusion—an
[argument]{.vocab}. So:

<!--
:::illustration
```graphviz
digraph {
  graph [layout = dot, rankdir = TB, fontname = "Georgia"];
  node [shape = box, fontname = "Georgia", fontsize = "10pt"];
  pr [label = "premises"];
  conc [label = "conclusion"];
  pr -> conc; 
}
```
:::
-->

