And we call this sort of visual representation of an argument an [Argument
Map]{.vocab}.

::: vaside
[Argument map]{.vocab}: a visual representation of an argument or several related
arguments. Especially useful for visualizing the logical structure of a
complex debate. [philmaps.com](philmaps.com){target="_blank"
rel="noopener noreferrer"} is provides some cool free online tools for
constructing argument maps.
:::

We will not be using argument maps in this course. I've introduced them here
as visual reinforcement for the idea we have been exploring: that an argument
always starts from some given premises, and leads to a conclusion.

Here are a few more examples of arguments. 

Suppose you see some dude wearing a Che Guevara
t-shirt, and infer that he is a communist.
Here is your argument, 
 represented as an argument map:

